    {"ev_id": "ev-conf-1860ab4d", "brief": {"key_ideas": ["Scatter logging overcomes the last mile between log-structured filesystems and persistent memory", "Existing PM LFSes maintain log structure optimized for block I/O but PM provides byte-addressable interface", "Scatter logging distributes log entries across PM to exploit byte-addressability and avoid sequential bottleneck", "Achieves high write performance with lightweight crash consistency on persistent memory"], "relevance": "Directly extends Linux filesystem design for persistent memory. Log-structured filesystems on PM inherit block I/O assumptions that PM doesn't require. Scatter logging uses PM's byte-addressability for non-sequential logging — relevant to the kernel's DAX (Direct Access) path, PM-aware filesystems, and crash consistency protocols. Published at EuroSys.", "methodology": "EuroSys. Persistent memory filesystem design. Scatter logging for byte-addressable PM. Crash consistency evaluation."}, "concepts": ["Virtual Filesystem Switch", "Block Device Layer"], "claims": [{"kind": "Proposal", "id_prefix": "prop", "name": "Scatter logging for persistent memory file systems", "description": "Distributes log entries across persistent memory to exploit byte-addressability rather than maintaining sequential log structure from block I/O era. Achieves high write performance with lightweight crash consistency."}]},

